WEBVTT

00:03.041 --> 00:06.291
-[ Thunder crashes ]
<i>-♪ I've got your number, lonely ♪</i>

00:06.375 --> 00:09.709
<i>♪ October 33 ♪</i>

00:09.792 --> 00:12.041
Jackson: <i>It's a natural</i>
<i>progression in any profession</i>

00:12.125 --> 00:14.000
<i>for the student to become the teacher,</i>

00:14.083 --> 00:16.375
<i>the mentee to become the mentor.</i>

00:16.458 --> 00:17.709
[ Thunder crashes ]

00:17.792 --> 00:22.542
<i>♪ Holds me down,</i>
<i>like you know how, darlin' ♪</i>

00:22.625 --> 00:24.542
<i>♪ Hold me now ♪</i>

00:25.417 --> 00:27.792
<i>♪ Like you know my plight ♪</i>

00:27.875 --> 00:29.667
<i>♪ Got your number ♪</i>

00:29.750 --> 00:31.333
[ Thunder crashes ]

00:34.083 --> 00:36.041
<i>It's not that much different</i>
<i>from parenting.</i>

00:36.125 --> 00:37.291
I'm your son.

00:40.041 --> 00:43.333
<i>We learn from our ancestors</i>
<i>how to make the perfect soup.</i>

00:44.375 --> 00:47.166
<i>♪ I'm sending love where you are at ♪</i>

00:48.083 --> 00:50.709
<i>How to soothe an aching head or heart.</i>

00:50.917 --> 00:52.500
Woman: <i>Your call has been forwarded</i>

00:52.583 --> 00:54.917
<i>to an automated voice messaging system.</i>

00:55.000 --> 00:58.208
-[ Cellphone beeps ]
<i>-♪ October 33 ♪</i>

00:58.792 --> 01:01.083
<i>♪ Your love's my only good thing ♪</i>

01:01.166 --> 01:03.792
<i>♪ Like, fair, fair, fair ♪</i>

01:04.375 --> 01:07.792
<i>♪ So, help me hear the bird sing ♪</i>

01:07.875 --> 01:10.542
<i>♪ I'll help you capture your dream ♪</i>

01:10.625 --> 01:13.542
<i>♪ Let's see it in the present ♪</i>

01:13.625 --> 01:15.625
<i>♪ And try to let it be ♪</i>

01:15.875 --> 01:19.709
<i>♪ I, I've got your number, lonely ♪</i>

01:19.875 --> 01:23.041
<i>♪ October 33 ♪</i>

01:25.750 --> 01:28.083
<i>♪ Like, fair, fair, fair ♪</i>

01:28.166 --> 01:30.625
Jackson: <i>We measure milestones</i>
<i>and percentiles</i>

01:30.709 --> 01:32.333
<i>-and first steps...</i>
-[ Bell jingles ]

01:32.417 --> 01:35.959
<i>...to try and gain insight into</i>
<i>the person they'll grow into.</i>

01:36.041 --> 01:37.583
[ Knocks on door ]

01:37.667 --> 01:40.041
-Hello?
<i>-♪ October 33 ♪</i>

01:40.291 --> 01:42.333
Man: Tate, you're early.

01:42.417 --> 01:44.875
I've just started packing lunches.

01:47.542 --> 01:49.041
[ Groans ]

01:51.250 --> 01:52.750
<i>♪ Crying in the back ♪</i>

01:52.834 --> 01:55.041
<i>As if knowing a bunch of numbers on charts</i>

01:55.125 --> 01:58.166
<i>is any true measure of what</i>
<i>we might make of ourselves.</i>

01:58.875 --> 02:00.375
Jackson.

02:00.458 --> 02:01.458
<i>♪ I do, to you ♪</i>

02:02.208 --> 02:03.625
Hey, Dad.

02:03.709 --> 02:06.291
<i>♪ Hold on ♪</i>

02:06.375 --> 02:07.917
<i>♪ Hold on ♪</i>

02:08.000 --> 02:09.750
[ Thunder crashes ]

02:09.834 --> 02:11.500
<i>♪ Hold on ♪</i>

02:11.583 --> 02:14.959
<i>♪ Fair, fair, fair ♪</i>

02:16.083 --> 02:17.333
<i>♪ Hold on ♪</i>

02:17.417 --> 02:19.917
[ Engine shuts off, music stops ]

02:22.750 --> 02:25.166
[ Thunder crashes ]

02:29.000 --> 02:30.542
[ Doorbell rings ]

02:30.625 --> 02:32.667
Alright. I know it seems, like,
impulsive and out of nowhere,

02:32.750 --> 02:35.041
but it's not -- it's just, uh...

02:35.125 --> 02:36.417
uh, fast.

02:36.500 --> 02:38.875
But it's not, like...

02:38.959 --> 02:40.792
impulsive, impulsive. It's...

02:42.542 --> 02:45.166
I thought it through. It's just
I thought it through --

02:45.250 --> 02:46.583
[ Thunder crashes ]

02:46.667 --> 02:48.000
Oh!

02:51.834 --> 02:53.125
[ Gasps ]

02:55.875 --> 02:57.959
[ Thunder crashes ]

03:06.417 --> 03:08.000
[ Dog barks in distance ]

03:09.875 --> 03:11.208
Everybody alive?

03:11.291 --> 03:13.834
Yeah. Yeah, yeah. That's not --

03:13.959 --> 03:15.500
[ Clears throat ] Not why I'm here.

03:15.583 --> 03:16.792
I thought you were Tate.

03:16.875 --> 03:19.792
He delivers meals for me to people in
the community that need them.

03:20.208 --> 03:21.875
Okay. Not Tate.

03:22.500 --> 03:24.166
Well, come on in. Take a load off.

03:24.250 --> 03:27.375
I tested clean yesterday
and haven't seen anyone.

03:27.458 --> 03:28.959
I haven't seen anyone, either.

03:29.041 --> 03:30.458
I just made a fresh pot of coffee.

03:30.542 --> 03:32.542
-Want some?
-I'm good.

03:33.792 --> 03:35.083
How have you been?

03:35.750 --> 03:37.417
I've been thinking a lot about you lately,

03:37.500 --> 03:39.166
what with everything going on
in the world.

03:39.250 --> 03:40.500
I was gonna call,

03:40.583 --> 03:42.041
but the way we left things last time,

03:42.125 --> 03:43.959
I figured you did not want to talk to me.

03:44.041 --> 03:48.709
And I didn't want to be
one of those added things

03:48.792 --> 03:50.959
on top of the pandemic to deal with.

03:53.500 --> 03:54.792
How have you been?

03:54.875 --> 03:56.458
How's your little girl?

03:56.542 --> 03:57.959
She must be, what...

03:58.041 --> 04:00.041
She's 3 1/2 years old.
Her name is Harriet.

04:00.125 --> 04:01.208
Right.

04:03.917 --> 04:06.166
Look, I didn't travel all this way

04:06.250 --> 04:09.208
to just catch up, so, um...

04:09.291 --> 04:10.917
I need...answers.

04:11.083 --> 04:14.125
Well, I've got about 150 lunches
to put together,

04:14.208 --> 04:15.542
so if we're gonna talk,

04:15.625 --> 04:19.041
why don't you grab a pair of gloves over
here with me and, uh...

04:19.125 --> 04:20.750
help me out?

04:21.834 --> 04:23.333
[ Thunder crashes ]

04:23.417 --> 04:25.375
Oh, my God, it's your night.

04:25.458 --> 04:26.792
It's -- Wait -- It's your night?

04:26.875 --> 04:28.417
How can it be your night with Harriet?

04:28.500 --> 04:30.875
She's not packed, she's not ready,
she's sick, and I have a calendar.

04:30.959 --> 04:32.375
It's okay, no, no, it's not --
it's not my night.

04:32.458 --> 04:33.542
No? Alright? April, hey.

04:33.625 --> 04:34.959
-It's not?
-No, no, no, it's alright.

04:35.041 --> 04:36.083
-Okay.
-Just take a breath.

04:36.166 --> 04:37.583
What's going on? What's wrong?

04:37.667 --> 04:40.375
She has a temp of 102,
and -- and she's coughing...

04:40.458 --> 04:41.792
-...and she has no appetite.
-Come here.

04:41.875 --> 04:43.458
But I-I took a rapid test --
it's not COVID.

04:43.542 --> 04:45.250
Come here, munchkin.
Come here. That's good.

04:45.333 --> 04:46.792
-Hey. Why didn't you call me?
-I don't know what it is.

04:46.875 --> 04:48.834
Whooping cough or RSV or rickets?

04:48.917 --> 04:50.709
-It's not rickets.
-People get rickets, Jackson.

04:50.792 --> 04:52.542
And -- And Matthew
just went out East with Ruby

04:52.625 --> 04:53.750
to see his sister,

04:53.834 --> 04:54.917
and the power keeps going on and off,

04:55.000 --> 04:56.291
and I know, I am a doctor,

04:56.375 --> 04:58.000
I need to take a deep breath
and I should be cool,

04:58.083 --> 04:59.709
-but I am --
-You're not being cool right now.

04:59.792 --> 05:01.250
You're not even breathing, okay?
Go ahead.

05:01.333 --> 05:02.875
Oh, God. She's been sick before,
obviously,

05:02.959 --> 05:05.583
but, like, COVID just makes
everything feel so...big.

05:05.667 --> 05:06.792
And I know I need to calm down,

05:06.875 --> 05:08.083
but no one in the history of calming down

05:08.166 --> 05:09.750
has ever calmed down by being told
to calm down, so I'm not gonna, okay?

05:09.834 --> 05:10.750
I'm not gonna tell you
to calm down, alright?

05:10.834 --> 05:12.208
I'm not telling you to calm
down, I promise. I just...

05:12.291 --> 05:13.583
Why don't you let me in the house, maybe?

05:13.667 --> 05:15.333
-Yeah, yes, okay. Just -- sorry.
-Okay?

05:15.417 --> 05:17.417
-Come in.
-Hey, sweetheart.

05:18.333 --> 05:19.875
I can't tell you how long it took me

05:19.959 --> 05:22.041
to come up with this nifty system.

05:22.125 --> 05:23.500
First, we start with a bunch of these,

05:23.583 --> 05:25.750
what I've coined the brawn bundle.

05:25.834 --> 05:28.792
Here's how we do it --
two pieces of smoked ham,

05:28.875 --> 05:32.458
one slice of honey turkey, and provolone.

05:32.542 --> 05:33.750
Are you serious with all this?

05:33.834 --> 05:36.291
Roll it up, and once you have
your ingredients set,

05:36.375 --> 05:37.583
you move down here to the bread.

05:37.667 --> 05:40.917
You won't believe
how much time that saves.

05:41.000 --> 05:42.125
Try a piece.

05:42.208 --> 05:44.542
Look, I'll make
the damn sandwiches with you

05:44.625 --> 05:46.250
in order to -- it's fine.

05:46.333 --> 05:49.041
Okay?
But I don't need to taste anything

05:49.125 --> 05:50.458
or have any food or coffee.

05:50.542 --> 05:52.709
Just -- I don't need anything
from you, honestly.

05:52.792 --> 05:53.959
I just need answers.

05:54.333 --> 05:55.709
[ Dog barking in distance ]

05:55.792 --> 05:57.000
Okay.

05:59.333 --> 06:01.625
Answers?

06:02.250 --> 06:05.125
Mom said something to me
that I cannot get out of my head.

06:05.208 --> 06:06.875
Yeah, she has a talent for that.

06:06.959 --> 06:09.542
She said, for the first time ever,

06:09.625 --> 06:11.583
that I sounded like you.

06:11.667 --> 06:13.542
[ Chuckles ] Did you piss her off?

06:13.625 --> 06:15.166
I said I can't really see change

06:15.250 --> 06:17.000
coming from inside the foundation.

06:17.083 --> 06:19.041
-There's too much bureaucracy.
-Well, to be honest,

06:19.125 --> 06:21.834
I haven't thought about
the foundation in a long time.

06:21.917 --> 06:23.959
Yeah, but what do you think
she meant by that?

06:24.041 --> 06:25.709
Years ago, I learned

06:25.792 --> 06:27.875
to never put words in your mother's mouth.

06:27.959 --> 06:29.208
If you had to guess.

06:30.458 --> 06:32.667
I've never been one for the establishment.

06:33.625 --> 06:35.625
I always thought
the whole system is rigged.

06:36.709 --> 06:38.583
So, how we doing over there?

06:39.792 --> 06:40.875
You know, I don't think

06:40.959 --> 06:43.125
ham-and-turkey sandwiches
get enough credit.

06:43.208 --> 06:45.500
They're simple, but they get the job done.

06:45.583 --> 06:48.375
So I said that
the whole system's just broken,

06:48.458 --> 06:50.250
needs to be thrown out and rebuilt,

06:50.333 --> 06:52.625
understanding that
that's damn near impossible

06:52.709 --> 06:54.291
considering how many people
benefit from it

06:54.375 --> 06:55.875
the way it is right now.

06:55.959 --> 06:57.542
That does sound a little like me.

07:01.458 --> 07:03.792
You look like you could use
some more turkey.

07:04.041 --> 07:05.834
Ever use a commercial meat slicer?

07:05.917 --> 07:08.500
-When would I have done that?
-Summer job?

07:09.667 --> 07:11.875
Anyway, it reminds me of the O.R.,

07:12.709 --> 07:15.417
without the pressure
of possibly killing someone.

07:15.500 --> 07:16.583
Come on, let me show you.

07:23.000 --> 07:25.333
Yeah, I can figure it out, thank you.

07:25.417 --> 07:26.625
Okay.

07:26.709 --> 07:28.291
[ Dog barking in distance ]

07:30.959 --> 07:32.291
You might want to --

07:32.375 --> 07:34.041
You might want to turn it on first.

07:34.250 --> 07:35.834
Yeah, right.

07:35.917 --> 07:38.792
[ Motor whirring ]

07:39.500 --> 07:40.792
Just, what is it?

07:40.875 --> 07:42.333
Here, let me show you. Okay.

07:42.417 --> 07:44.375
First of all, you gotta lift this.

07:44.458 --> 07:45.750
Here's your gauge for how thick

07:45.834 --> 07:47.125
you want to make the slice of meat.

07:47.208 --> 07:48.333
Okay. Got it. Thank you.

07:48.417 --> 07:49.917
-The carriage goes back and forth.
-Great.

07:50.000 --> 07:51.625
[ Motor whirring ]

07:51.709 --> 07:52.959
I got it.

07:56.125 --> 07:58.583
Kinda relaxing when you get
a rhythm going, huh?

07:59.458 --> 08:03.166
So...you're saying you wanted change,
but what?

08:03.250 --> 08:04.834
You felt powerless
'cause you were an Avery or...?

08:04.917 --> 08:05.792
As you know,

08:05.875 --> 08:07.375
the Avery name carries
a great deal of influence,

08:07.458 --> 08:08.709
but it also carries...

08:09.458 --> 08:10.834
a great deal of baggage.

08:10.917 --> 08:12.208
That amount of money

08:12.291 --> 08:14.417
can become a burden pretty quickly.

08:14.500 --> 08:16.667
Everybody knows you have it, so...

08:16.750 --> 08:19.041
they expect you to be responsible

08:19.125 --> 08:20.333
to fix everything with it.

08:20.417 --> 08:22.500
And there's almost no one in your shoes,

08:22.625 --> 08:24.792
so almost no one seems to get it.

08:24.875 --> 08:26.542
At least not when I said it.

08:26.625 --> 08:29.208
Certainly not when the name is synonymous

08:29.291 --> 08:31.375
with just the worst behavior imaginable.

08:31.458 --> 08:34.875
Well, not here it's not.

08:34.959 --> 08:36.792
Here, nobody knows who my father was

08:36.875 --> 08:38.208
or that I come from money.

08:38.834 --> 08:40.250
Out here, they just think

08:40.333 --> 08:43.166
I'm Robert who runs the diner.

08:44.500 --> 08:48.083
[ Thunder crashes ]

08:48.166 --> 08:49.500
April: God.

08:49.583 --> 08:52.041
Uh, Matthew's been working a lot.

08:52.125 --> 08:53.542
I mean, I've been working a lot.

08:53.625 --> 08:55.542
Yeah, don't worry about it.
My place is, uh --

08:55.625 --> 08:56.500
Please don't do that.

08:56.583 --> 08:58.417
Don't be all weird-nice
with your voice an octave higher

08:58.500 --> 09:00.583
like you do with people
at hotels or at the bank.

09:00.667 --> 09:02.625
I have a weird bank voice now?

09:02.709 --> 09:03.917
It's making you nuts.

09:04.000 --> 09:05.333
[ Chuckling ] You -- You can say it.

09:05.417 --> 09:07.041
Just mess everywhere.

09:07.125 --> 09:08.542
Pillows all over the place.

09:08.625 --> 09:09.875
I maintain that throw pillows

09:09.959 --> 09:11.583
are useless and stupid, yeah.

09:12.250 --> 09:14.667
How long has my munchkin been sick?

09:14.750 --> 09:16.625
[ April sighs ] Couple days.

09:17.250 --> 09:18.959
She just hasn't wanted to do anything,

09:19.041 --> 09:20.250
just lie on me.

09:20.333 --> 09:21.959
Also, she needs a bath.
She smells like feet.

09:22.041 --> 09:23.583
Well, I hate to break it
to you -- that's you.

09:23.667 --> 09:25.375
-No, it's not.
-100 percent you.

09:25.458 --> 09:26.625
[ Sniffing ]

09:26.709 --> 09:28.625
-Oh, God. That is me.
-Jackson: Yeah.

09:28.709 --> 09:30.834
-Go take a shower.
-April [ sighs ]: Jackson, I --

09:30.917 --> 09:33.041
April, go take a shower, please.

09:34.750 --> 09:36.625
-Hey, Jackson.
-Mm-hmm?

09:36.709 --> 09:37.792
I'm calming down.

09:37.875 --> 09:39.583
-See?
-I am. I am.

09:39.667 --> 09:41.709
-10 minutes.
-10 minutes.

09:41.792 --> 09:44.542
She ever taken
a 10-minute shower in her life?

09:44.625 --> 09:45.875
I don't think so.

09:46.709 --> 09:48.208
Some tunes? Good idea.

09:48.792 --> 09:50.709
Let's see what she's got.

09:54.667 --> 09:57.875
[ Jazz music plays ]

09:59.959 --> 10:02.458
We got this, right?

10:02.542 --> 10:04.750
We got this, baby.

10:04.834 --> 10:06.166
We got this.

10:06.250 --> 10:08.333
You're gonna feel better in no time.

10:08.417 --> 10:10.250
Harriet and Dad.

10:11.125 --> 10:12.792
-We got this.
-[ Thunder crashes ]

10:12.875 --> 10:14.083
[ Electricity crackles ]

10:14.166 --> 10:15.709
April: Oh, come on!

10:15.792 --> 10:17.333
Or maybe we don't.

10:17.625 --> 10:21.083
[ John Moran's
"Thousand Watt Workout" plays ]

10:21.166 --> 10:25.375
<i>♪ Looking like a fisherman ♪</i>

10:25.458 --> 10:28.333
<i>♪ I'm dropping a line in the sea ♪</i>

10:30.291 --> 10:32.250
I gotta give it to you --
that's some good turkey.

10:32.333 --> 10:33.542
Best in the state.

10:33.625 --> 10:35.500
Yeah, I'll take your word for it.

10:35.583 --> 10:36.917
<i>♪ Hoping that the graying skies ♪</i>

10:37.000 --> 10:38.166
So, what'd your dad think

10:38.250 --> 10:40.041
when you decided to walk away from it all?

10:40.125 --> 10:42.667
At first, he thought it was just a phase.

10:42.750 --> 10:44.709
But then when he realized I was serious,

10:45.500 --> 10:47.625
he stopped speaking to me.

10:47.709 --> 10:48.834
Completely?

10:48.917 --> 10:51.000
He said I was selfish, compulsive, lazy,

10:51.083 --> 10:53.291
a stain on the family name.

10:53.375 --> 10:57.083
Which I now see is such a complete joke.

10:57.166 --> 11:00.041
No, he was never interested
in talking to me,

11:00.125 --> 11:02.709
unless it was about the hospital image

11:02.792 --> 11:04.625
or profits or expansion.

11:04.709 --> 11:06.208
If I have to have one more conversation

11:06.291 --> 11:08.500
about cutting hospital costs, I swear...

11:08.583 --> 11:09.875
Someone's got to do it.

11:09.959 --> 11:11.667
I just knew it wasn't gonna be me.

11:11.750 --> 11:14.792
I was never gonna be
the son my father wanted

11:14.875 --> 11:17.625
because I didn't want to be
the man the role required.

11:21.875 --> 11:23.333
That's why you're here.

11:24.083 --> 11:25.667
-Why's that?
-Because...

11:26.166 --> 11:28.166
you're ready to leave it all behind.

11:28.250 --> 11:29.458
[ Motor whirring ]

11:41.041 --> 11:42.750
[ Sighs ]

11:42.834 --> 11:44.667
Why does anyone have
an electric water heater?

11:44.750 --> 11:47.291
A power outage is when
you need hot water the most.

11:47.375 --> 11:50.250
Well, Harriet cried herself to sleep.

11:50.333 --> 11:52.417
I propped her head up
to help with the coughing.

11:52.500 --> 11:53.709
Okay, thank you.

11:53.792 --> 11:56.208
And I found a flashlight
and a few candles,

11:56.291 --> 11:58.000
but I can't find any
damn matches in this house.

11:58.083 --> 12:00.083
Oh, yeah, well, I'm married
to a first responder.

12:00.166 --> 12:02.417
The matches are in a drawer
even I've never found.

12:02.500 --> 12:04.792
Alright. Well, then, stove it is.

12:04.875 --> 12:06.834
-[ Clicking ]
-April: Geez.

12:06.917 --> 12:08.542
Can you get some more candles?

12:08.625 --> 12:10.041
[ Chuckles ]

12:10.125 --> 12:11.583
What?

12:13.208 --> 12:14.500
Oh, crap! Sorry.

12:14.583 --> 12:16.000
This is a nun.

12:16.083 --> 12:18.458
-I just grabbed the, uh --
-The first nun you could find?

12:18.542 --> 12:20.458
[ Sighs ] Saying I'm going to hell?

12:20.542 --> 12:22.458
-Since when do you believe in hell?
-True.

12:22.625 --> 12:24.375
But they're your candles,
so you're going to hell.

12:24.458 --> 12:25.917
Okay. [ Chuckles ]

12:26.000 --> 12:28.250
-Alright, just give me this.
-Yeah, grab that.

12:28.333 --> 12:29.500
Her fever's at 102,

12:29.583 --> 12:31.917
so you might be right about RSV.

12:32.000 --> 12:34.917
Okay. So we just
give her acetaminophen

12:35.000 --> 12:36.917
and wait it out
unless she gets short of breath?

12:37.000 --> 12:39.083
Versus driving in a blackout
to Grey-Sloan in a pandemic?

12:39.166 --> 12:40.542
Yeah, we're not going anywhere.

12:40.625 --> 12:42.000
The risk of exposure alone...

12:42.083 --> 12:44.291
We don't need doctors, April.
We <i>are </i>doctors.

12:44.375 --> 12:45.500
And if she gets worse...

12:45.583 --> 12:46.792
Which she probably won't.

12:46.875 --> 12:47.875
Exactly.

12:47.959 --> 12:50.041
Yeah.

12:50.667 --> 12:52.291
How's Meredith doing?

12:52.375 --> 12:53.750
I've been praying for her.

12:53.834 --> 12:55.834
-Oh, she's, uh -- She's awake.
-Yeah?

12:55.917 --> 12:57.709
And she's getting better
every day, stronger.

12:57.792 --> 12:58.834
-Oh.
-Yeah.

13:00.166 --> 13:02.458
So, tonight wasn't your night.

13:02.542 --> 13:04.792
Yes. As usual,
your calendar is impeccable.

13:04.875 --> 13:05.834
Well done.

13:05.917 --> 13:07.625
No, I'm just saying, uh, tonight --

13:07.709 --> 13:09.542
tonight wasn't your night,
so why are you --

13:09.625 --> 13:11.500
How have I never been to your place?

13:11.583 --> 13:13.542
I feel like I guess
we must always do drop-offs

13:13.625 --> 13:14.750
at mine or work.

13:14.834 --> 13:16.625
It's -- It's nice. It looks really nice.

13:16.709 --> 13:18.166
-I like what you've done.
-Jackson...

13:18.250 --> 13:20.000
You guys are happy,
you and -- you and Matthew?

13:20.083 --> 13:21.667
We're busy, like everyone else.

13:21.750 --> 13:23.333
And Harriet and you and him and Ruby,

13:23.417 --> 13:25.250
the same house, it's going...

13:25.375 --> 13:27.125
Exposed brick is -- is cool.
I know you've always liked --

13:27.208 --> 13:28.375
Do you really think I can't tell
when you're being cagey?

13:28.458 --> 13:30.667
-I'm not being cagey.
-Am I happy?

13:30.750 --> 13:32.542
Exposed brick? Would you just
talk like a person?

13:33.917 --> 13:35.333
[ Sighs ]

13:36.625 --> 13:37.959
I went to see my dad again.

13:38.041 --> 13:39.166
Oh, God. Is he sick?

13:39.250 --> 13:40.792
No, he's the same as always.

13:40.875 --> 13:43.792
Obliviously medium happy about
his obliviously medium life.

13:45.291 --> 13:46.959
I thought you never
wanted to see him again.

13:47.041 --> 13:48.458
I didn't.

13:48.959 --> 13:51.458
I needed to know if I was right
about what I...

13:52.417 --> 13:53.625
what I wanted.

13:54.458 --> 13:56.041
And we're back to being cagey.

13:56.125 --> 13:57.667
I'm not trying to be cagey, April.

13:58.291 --> 14:00.250
April, he couldn't handle it.

14:00.959 --> 14:05.000
Okay? He couldn't step up
or step into his own,

14:05.083 --> 14:06.458
and I can.

14:06.583 --> 14:07.875
[ Thunder rumbles ]

14:07.959 --> 14:10.291
I want to take over the foundation.

14:13.917 --> 14:16.875
Is this the, uh, coffee you showed me
last time I was here?

14:16.959 --> 14:18.625
We sold out of our first batch.

14:18.709 --> 14:20.458
The local paper wrote us up,

14:20.542 --> 14:22.917
so we decided to add four more roasts.

14:23.000 --> 14:25.250
I was gonna branch out
into other parts of the state,

14:25.333 --> 14:27.375
and then, ah, COVID.

14:27.458 --> 14:29.709
Yeah, I remember.
You guys got hit pretty hard.

14:29.792 --> 14:31.417
Hospital was turning people away, right?

14:31.500 --> 14:32.834
It was a lot.

14:32.917 --> 14:34.458
I did everything I could

14:34.542 --> 14:36.166
to keep this place open after COVID hit.

14:36.250 --> 14:40.208
But then I ended up just bagging up food
for the regulars.

14:40.291 --> 14:41.375
Word spread,

14:41.458 --> 14:43.417
and every morning, I come in here

14:43.500 --> 14:46.333
and crank up the Doobie Brothers,

14:46.417 --> 14:48.041
start packing lunches.

14:48.125 --> 14:50.667
It was weirdly therapeutic.

14:50.750 --> 14:52.000
Kept my mind occupied.

14:52.083 --> 14:54.041
[ Sighs ] Well...

14:54.125 --> 14:56.083
you got quite the bubble out here.

14:56.166 --> 14:58.458
Built a very different life for yourself.

14:58.542 --> 14:59.667
Robert: We're all raised to think

14:59.750 --> 15:01.667
that's some kind of wild concept.

15:01.750 --> 15:04.250
But what's wild is going to work every day

15:04.333 --> 15:06.166
doing something you do not like,

15:06.250 --> 15:08.250
thinking one day,
it'll just magically stop.

15:09.375 --> 15:10.458
Yeah.

15:11.667 --> 15:13.709
-I just feel stuck.
-Hmm.

15:15.583 --> 15:17.709
Like there's two of me.
Like there's this --

15:17.792 --> 15:20.959
this successful surgeon
that I worked so hard to become,

15:21.041 --> 15:24.166
was trying to push the foundation
to be more progressive.

15:24.250 --> 15:26.041
[ Sighs ] And also just the guy

15:26.125 --> 15:29.250
that didn't ask for any of this, you know?

15:29.333 --> 15:31.625
I'm worried that maybe it's too late --

15:32.542 --> 15:34.667
the system's beyond repair.

15:35.333 --> 15:38.083
Maybe I could be effective
from the outside.

15:38.166 --> 15:40.041
Or maybe you could let go of the idea

15:40.166 --> 15:42.834
that it's your job to save the world.

15:44.458 --> 15:47.667
You know, there's nothing wrong
with wanting to keep things simpler.

15:47.750 --> 15:49.583
Yeah, I think about that a lot.

15:50.166 --> 15:51.959
Actually, I think, you know,

15:52.041 --> 15:54.625
I could get a small place in the woods,

15:54.709 --> 15:56.667
maybe open a private practice,

15:56.750 --> 15:59.792
do things [Chuckling] I really care about.

15:59.875 --> 16:02.667
Explore the great outdoors with Harriet.

16:03.208 --> 16:05.875
We all deserve to live our lives
however we want.

16:05.959 --> 16:07.000
Sure, yeah.

16:07.083 --> 16:09.250
You are an older white guy
who's always had money, so...

16:09.333 --> 16:11.083
If nothing changes in the world,

16:11.166 --> 16:13.667
you're still gonna be fine,
but I -- I hear you.

16:13.750 --> 16:16.542
You given any thought to what if?

16:16.625 --> 16:18.208
What if I didn't come back here?

16:18.291 --> 16:20.083
What if you chose differently, yeah.

16:22.250 --> 16:24.458
Well, I'm more of a, hmm...

16:26.250 --> 16:27.792
"never look back" type.

16:31.583 --> 16:33.250
Right, yeah.

16:34.792 --> 16:36.083
Yeah, um...

16:40.417 --> 16:43.709
When I was here last time,
I wanted to ask you why,

16:43.792 --> 16:45.750
and I -- I didn't -- I couldn't --

16:45.834 --> 16:47.583
I guess I used to say I was over it,

16:47.667 --> 16:48.792
but I'm not.

16:48.875 --> 16:50.208
I need to know why you left.

16:53.166 --> 16:54.667
'Cause, um...

16:57.417 --> 16:59.667
...I realize that
it's really messed me up...

17:00.417 --> 17:01.542
pretty badly.

17:01.625 --> 17:03.333
And, um...

17:03.417 --> 17:06.333
[ Clears throat ]
It just made it hard to, like,

17:06.417 --> 17:08.375
maintain relationships and stuff.

17:09.333 --> 17:11.750
Having this inclination
to run away all the time.

17:11.834 --> 17:12.834
And I know, I know --

17:12.917 --> 17:14.583
running away
doesn't actually solve anything.

17:14.667 --> 17:15.959
I know that.

17:17.333 --> 17:19.208
So -- And I've tried.

17:19.291 --> 17:23.083
I've tried really hard
to rid myself of the shame

17:23.458 --> 17:25.917
and the pain that comes with
all that, and, uh...

17:26.000 --> 17:27.792
You know, just kind of doubled-down

17:27.875 --> 17:30.583
on being the best at everything --

17:30.667 --> 17:32.333
the best father I could possibly be.

17:32.417 --> 17:34.625
I probably stayed in my marriage
longer than I should have,

17:34.709 --> 17:36.166
went along with foundation business

17:36.250 --> 17:37.542
longer than I should have,

17:37.625 --> 17:39.375
but no matter what,
[Grunts] when it gets rough,

17:39.458 --> 17:42.083
I just end up... right there,

17:42.542 --> 17:44.375
running, into the woods.

17:44.458 --> 17:46.542
Try to fight the you in me.

17:46.750 --> 17:49.041
[ Motor whirring ]

17:49.125 --> 17:51.792
Can you not just sit there looking at me?
Can you say something?

17:52.000 --> 17:53.542
Pretend that I'm worth talking to?

17:53.625 --> 17:55.542
I don't know how you can just
say nothing all the -- Ow!

17:55.625 --> 17:57.709
God! Aah! Damn it!

17:58.834 --> 17:59.959
God!

18:00.041 --> 18:01.291
Oh, man. You alright?

18:01.375 --> 18:03.458
No, I'm not alright! Give it -- I got it!

18:03.542 --> 18:05.166
Pressure, pressure, pressure.

18:12.625 --> 18:14.125
Okay.

18:20.625 --> 18:22.583
[ Sighs ] Temp's down to 101.

18:22.667 --> 18:24.333
-It's just a bad dream.
-[ Thunder rumbles ]

18:24.417 --> 18:26.834
-Oh, yeah? How's her breathing?
-It's better.

18:26.917 --> 18:28.000
-Oh, good, alright.
-Yeah.

18:28.083 --> 18:30.166
-So we could be out of the woods.
-Yeah.

18:31.542 --> 18:33.083
[ Thunder rumbling ]

18:33.750 --> 18:35.083
So, were you hoping

18:35.166 --> 18:36.792
-Matthew wasn't gonna be here tonight?
-What?

18:36.875 --> 18:38.125
No, I don't have a problem with Matthew.

18:38.208 --> 18:39.750
-Really?
-[ Chuckling ] What?

18:39.834 --> 18:41.500
Whenever you guys
are in the same room together,

18:41.583 --> 18:42.875
you say one of three things --

18:42.959 --> 18:45.000
"Yup," "Sure," "Not a problem."

18:45.083 --> 18:46.041
Jackson: Well, okay, yeah.

18:46.125 --> 18:49.417
We're not best friends,
but, I mean, it's civil.

18:49.500 --> 18:50.959
He seems like a fine guy.

18:51.041 --> 18:54.792
-He seems, uh, kind.
-Kind?

18:54.875 --> 18:56.542
I don't have a <i>bad </i>word to say about him.

18:56.625 --> 18:57.875
That -- That's something.

18:57.959 --> 19:00.917
So then why did you want to
come tell me this in person?

19:02.000 --> 19:04.041
You're considering running the foundation.

19:04.125 --> 19:05.166
What's that got to do with me?

19:05.250 --> 19:06.500
That's the thing --

19:06.583 --> 19:09.959
I'm not just considering it.
I'm doing it.

19:11.250 --> 19:13.750
Running the foundation means
I got to move to Boston.

19:14.792 --> 19:17.667
W-- Without Harriet?

19:17.750 --> 19:19.125
No. God, no.

19:19.208 --> 19:20.333
I'm moving to Boston,

19:20.417 --> 19:23.458
and I really need you all to come.

19:24.375 --> 19:26.166
The foundation will employ
you and Matthew.

19:26.250 --> 19:27.208
You'll be set.

19:27.291 --> 19:28.333
You can do whatever you want

19:28.417 --> 19:31.125
in terms of an outreach program
or design or build.

19:31.208 --> 19:33.000
Anything you want to do, we'll fund it.

19:33.667 --> 19:36.000
-I would never leave Harriet.
-[ Thunder crashes ]

19:37.625 --> 19:40.583
I could never, ever leave Harriet,

19:40.667 --> 19:43.333
which means I really
need you all to come with me.

19:44.667 --> 19:45.959
Please.

19:46.375 --> 19:47.959
[ Thunder crashes ]

19:51.709 --> 19:54.375
Robert: Doesn't look like there are
any tendon injuries.

19:54.458 --> 19:55.792
Yeah, the cut's not that deep.

19:55.875 --> 19:58.250
Okay. Another wash, then let's glue it.

19:59.041 --> 20:00.125
[ Sighs ]

20:00.166 --> 20:01.583
I can handle it from here.

20:01.667 --> 20:02.875
Actually, just hand me the glue.

20:03.792 --> 20:05.000
Okay.

20:07.709 --> 20:09.000
Ow.

20:10.583 --> 20:11.917
[ Grunts softly ]

20:12.333 --> 20:13.875
Just give me your hand.

20:13.959 --> 20:16.291
-Come on, man. Let me do this.
-Okay.

20:17.083 --> 20:18.959
I may not have practiced in a while,

20:19.041 --> 20:21.208
but it is like riding a bike.

20:21.417 --> 20:23.542
Not exactly, but okay.

20:23.625 --> 20:25.375
Hold it together.

20:27.291 --> 20:28.417
See?

20:28.500 --> 20:30.333
Alright. That is not bad.

20:30.417 --> 20:31.834
Okay. Does it hurt?

20:31.917 --> 20:33.625
-Do you want any Tylenol or anything?
-Um.

20:33.709 --> 20:35.583
No, no, no. It's actually just...

20:35.959 --> 20:38.542
It stings a little bit, but that's fine.

20:38.625 --> 20:40.291
-Thank yo
-. Look at us.

20:40.375 --> 20:42.542
We ought to open up a family practice.

20:47.375 --> 20:48.667
You know, I'm gonna...

20:49.834 --> 20:51.792
I'm just gonna grab some air.

20:58.333 --> 21:00.083
-[ Thunder crashes ]
-April: <i>I get it, Jackson.</i>

21:00.166 --> 21:01.500
You're not the only person in quarantine

21:01.583 --> 21:03.250
who's drowning in big

21:03.333 --> 21:04.542
"What the hell am I doing with my life?"

21:04.625 --> 21:05.625
kind of questions.

21:05.709 --> 21:08.917
But you don't just up and move across
the country on a whim.

21:09.000 --> 21:10.875
No, no, no, that's not what
this is. It's not on a whim.

21:10.959 --> 21:13.125
Since the moment I met you at Mercy West,

21:13.208 --> 21:16.166
you have rejected
your family name, the legacy,

21:16.250 --> 21:17.542
even the freaking plane.

21:17.625 --> 21:19.542
You've -- You've wanted
nothing to do with any of it.

21:19.625 --> 21:21.250
-I resisted. That's not necess--
-No, no, no.

21:21.333 --> 21:23.208
Sorry, you've been running,
kicking and screaming.

21:23.250 --> 21:24.834
That is not where this is coming from.

21:24.917 --> 21:26.709
Okay? I can use this as an opportunity

21:26.792 --> 21:29.083
to make some profound changes
in the world.

21:29.166 --> 21:30.291
You understand?

21:30.375 --> 21:32.500
I respect that. I mean,
I-I admire that, Jackson.

21:32.583 --> 21:35.000
As long as it's not an inconvenience to
your perfect little life here?

21:35.083 --> 21:38.417
Uprooting my entire life
is not an inconvenience.

21:38.500 --> 21:40.208
Okay, you're right.

21:40.291 --> 21:42.041
But I need this.

21:42.125 --> 21:43.625
I know that I need to do this.

21:43.709 --> 21:45.792
I can feel it in my gut, and I just want
to trust that for once.

21:45.917 --> 21:48.834
Okay. How many times have you
"felt in your gut"...

21:48.917 --> 21:51.166
-Don't --
-...the need to just pack up a tent

21:51.250 --> 21:53.083
and go for a walkabout

21:53.166 --> 21:54.792
and talk to yourself amongst the trees?

21:54.875 --> 21:57.083
So I'm the only one that's walked away
when I was having a hard time?

21:57.959 --> 21:59.542
-Just me, huh?
-[ Sighs ]

21:59.625 --> 22:00.625
How many times have you been

22:00.709 --> 22:02.000
sitting in the front pew at a church,

22:02.083 --> 22:04.250
talking to God about the plans
for your life?

22:04.333 --> 22:06.125
-It's not the same thing. I --
-Why not?

22:06.208 --> 22:08.208
Why is it that you can find
solace and purpose in a church,

22:08.291 --> 22:09.500
but I can't find it in nature,

22:09.583 --> 22:12.000
where I can actually have
some time that's quiet,

22:12.083 --> 22:13.834
hear myself think,
think about what <i>I </i>want,

22:13.917 --> 22:15.333
not what everybody else expects of me?

22:15.417 --> 22:16.583
So how long did you spend

22:16.667 --> 22:19.333
thinking about going to see your father?

22:19.417 --> 22:21.250
-How much time did you spend doing that?
-Don't reduce it to that!

22:21.333 --> 22:22.750
Or did you just, like,
get in a car and -- and go --

22:22.834 --> 22:23.917
No, it's not on a whim, okay?

22:24.000 --> 22:25.041
-It was a realization.
-Okay, I --

22:25.125 --> 22:26.166
I needed clarity,

22:26.250 --> 22:28.333
and I went and talked to Robert,
and I got it.

22:28.417 --> 22:33.125
[ Sighs ] You have
never wanted any of this.

22:33.208 --> 22:36.291
And -- And I'm just
supposed to roll with it

22:36.375 --> 22:37.583
and see what happens?

22:37.917 --> 22:40.083
What -- What happens when you regret it?

22:40.166 --> 22:42.625
What happens when you realize
that you actually hate it?

22:42.709 --> 22:44.125
What you're asking of me,

22:44.208 --> 22:46.542
of -- of our family,
of our daughter, it's...

22:48.333 --> 22:50.875
[ Sighs ] What happens
if it doesn't work?

22:52.917 --> 22:55.500
Matthew got on one knee
and proposed to you...

22:55.583 --> 22:57.500
-Please don't. Jackson, I'm --
-No, no, no, it's true.

22:57.625 --> 22:59.500
He got on one knee and proposed to you
in front of me.

22:59.917 --> 23:01.166
I stood there,

23:01.875 --> 23:03.250
watched another man become your husband

23:03.333 --> 23:05.500
and stepfather to my child -- our child...

23:05.625 --> 23:06.542
Mm-hmm.

23:06.625 --> 23:08.375
...and at no point
did I come to you and say,

23:08.458 --> 23:10.208
"Yeah, but what if it doesn't work?"

23:10.291 --> 23:11.208
I didn't do that.

23:11.291 --> 23:12.875
I had your back that day
and every day since.

23:14.500 --> 23:16.250
He bugs the hell out of you, doesn't he?

23:16.333 --> 23:18.125
I'm allowed to be frustrated at the guy

23:18.208 --> 23:19.875
who makes sandwiches weird.

23:19.959 --> 23:21.917
Who -- I-It's -- And he
calls her Hair-Hair.

23:22.000 --> 23:24.875
-I know. I know. I'm working on that.
-[ Chuckles ]

23:25.834 --> 23:28.125
What I'm not allowed to do, April,

23:28.250 --> 23:30.041
what -- what I've actually never done,

23:30.125 --> 23:31.125
is stand in the way

23:31.208 --> 23:33.542
of the happiness
that you chose for yourself.

23:33.625 --> 23:35.083
[ Thunder rumbles ]

23:35.166 --> 23:36.458
I had your back.

23:37.291 --> 23:38.709
I know this is a surprise,

23:38.792 --> 23:41.583
but I'm just asking you --
do the same for me.

23:42.500 --> 23:44.041
-[ Thunder crashes ]
-I...

23:45.709 --> 23:48.291
I -- I want you to be happy, Jackson.

23:49.125 --> 23:50.583
You deserve it.

23:52.208 --> 23:55.583
But... running the foundation?

23:55.667 --> 23:58.834
I -- I'm sorry. It's just...

24:00.083 --> 24:01.500
You're not that guy.

24:01.834 --> 24:04.375
-[ Thunder rumbles ]
-I don't think you ever will be.

24:10.959 --> 24:13.333
Jackson: So, that's it?
I'm either gonna fail or quit?

24:13.417 --> 24:15.417
I'm sorry, Jackson. I didn't --
I didn't mean that --

24:15.500 --> 24:16.834
Yeah, you did.
That's exactly what you meant.

24:16.917 --> 24:20.458
[ Sighs ] Ok--
Fine. Yeah. I did.

24:21.166 --> 24:23.291
Jackson, you are a brilliant surgeon.

24:23.375 --> 24:25.917
You rebuild people's faces,
you rebuild their lives.

24:26.000 --> 24:27.125
You find a way to make them breathe

24:27.208 --> 24:28.917
when -- when it seems impossible.

24:29.333 --> 24:31.500
You gave a little boy back his hands.

24:31.583 --> 24:33.417
You prayed me back into the world

24:33.500 --> 24:34.959
when I was almost dead.

24:35.041 --> 24:37.166
Y-You take out impossible tumors,

24:37.250 --> 24:39.333
and you make people
walk out into the world

24:39.417 --> 24:41.166
with their heads held high.

24:41.250 --> 24:43.333
That's where you've left your mark.

24:44.041 --> 24:47.083
It's what makes you exceptional.
Wh--

24:47.542 --> 24:50.000
Why would you want to give all of that up?

24:50.083 --> 24:52.041
It's not about what I want.
It's what I need to do.

24:52.125 --> 24:53.875
Well, you know what? It's
a little late to decide that.

24:53.959 --> 24:54.834
Excuse me?

24:54.917 --> 24:56.583
You don't get to choose
who I am in this world, April.

24:56.667 --> 24:57.583
Nobody does.

24:57.667 --> 24:59.750
Not my father, not Mom -- nobody.

24:59.834 --> 25:01.542
And you don't get to choose
your career over mine.

25:01.625 --> 25:02.875
-That's --
-I am happy.

25:03.000 --> 25:04.083
I'm helping people.

25:04.166 --> 25:06.458
I'm really helping them.

25:06.583 --> 25:08.000
I am building support systems

25:08.083 --> 25:10.458
and resources for people
in rural communities,

25:10.542 --> 25:11.959
and they need so much,

25:12.041 --> 25:13.709
and I can actually do that for them.

25:13.792 --> 25:15.250
Jackson: And you can keep doing that.

25:15.333 --> 25:17.166
You can do it on an even bigger scale.

25:17.250 --> 25:18.542
You can do it across the country.

25:18.625 --> 25:20.834
I'm -- You're literally
just gaining resources.

25:20.917 --> 25:22.709
April, I am not trying
to diminish your work.

25:22.792 --> 25:24.250
We have an opportunity

25:24.333 --> 25:26.125
to do something really amazing
for all of us.

25:26.208 --> 25:28.041
Matthew will go along with it.

25:28.125 --> 25:30.000
He'll follow you.

25:30.083 --> 25:31.667
That's why I like him so much.

25:32.291 --> 25:34.250
[ Both laugh ]

25:34.333 --> 25:36.166
Oh, God.

25:40.750 --> 25:41.875
You know what?

25:41.959 --> 25:45.667
You -- You didn't always have my back.

25:48.250 --> 25:51.166
When I found what I needed in Jordan,

25:51.291 --> 25:52.250
you didn't go with me.

25:52.333 --> 25:54.125
You left me alone. I went alone.

25:54.208 --> 25:56.834
Jackson: April, that's not fair.
You ran away from me.

25:56.917 --> 25:59.667
And Samuel and the pain and the grief,

25:59.750 --> 26:02.291
which is understandable.

26:02.375 --> 26:05.583
You know, I was resentful at the time,
but I get it.

26:05.667 --> 26:07.166
You were surviving.

26:07.250 --> 26:09.500
You had to do
what you had to do to survive.

26:09.583 --> 26:11.875
But this isn't that, anyway.

26:11.959 --> 26:13.667
I'm not running <i>from </i>something.

26:14.166 --> 26:15.750
I'm trying to run <i>to </i>something.

26:15.834 --> 26:18.291
Trying to make something my own.

26:18.375 --> 26:19.917
[ Thunder rumbles ]

26:21.625 --> 26:23.125
[ Sighs ]

26:23.208 --> 26:25.750
It's not fair, Jackson.

26:26.834 --> 26:28.291
If you had the opportunity

26:28.375 --> 26:32.875
to finally make it all make sense...

26:34.166 --> 26:36.917
to become what you were meant to be,

26:37.000 --> 26:40.959
wouldn't you try really,
really hard to get there?

26:42.375 --> 26:43.959
I would.

26:44.500 --> 26:46.750
I did. [ Chuckles ]

26:46.834 --> 26:49.125
That's all I'm asking for.

26:52.291 --> 26:53.667
[ Sighs ]

26:53.750 --> 26:56.208
[ Harriet cries ]

26:56.291 --> 26:57.667
I got it.

26:57.750 --> 27:00.375
[ Crying continues ]

27:01.375 --> 27:03.542
[ Thunder rumbles ]

27:08.000 --> 27:11.125
[ Sighs ] 99.3.

27:11.208 --> 27:12.333
-Oh, good. Alright.
-Yeah.

27:12.417 --> 27:13.750
So she's a little more comfortable.

27:13.834 --> 27:15.375
Yeah. She's talking in her sleep.

27:15.458 --> 27:16.875
-Oh, yeah?
-Yeah.

27:16.959 --> 27:17.959
Anything good?

27:18.041 --> 27:19.542
Just gibberish.

27:19.625 --> 27:21.583
She said, "Amananome."

27:21.667 --> 27:23.667
Ah. That is the sea anemone.

27:23.750 --> 27:24.792
Oh.

27:24.875 --> 27:26.375
She's been waking me up the last few weeks

27:26.458 --> 27:28.625
with a different sea creature fact.

27:28.709 --> 27:29.792
Are they really "facts," though?

27:29.875 --> 27:32.250
[ Laughs ] In her head, they are.

27:32.333 --> 27:33.709
[ Chuckles ]

27:33.792 --> 27:35.959
It's the best alarm clock, ever,
I'll tell you.

27:36.041 --> 27:37.625
Last week, she told me

27:37.709 --> 27:40.792
that she could hear "werewoofs"
throwing up in your basement.

27:40.875 --> 27:42.375
Really? I don't even have a basement.

27:42.458 --> 27:43.625
Oh, I'm aware.

27:43.709 --> 27:45.375
There's no convincing her otherwise.

27:45.458 --> 27:46.917
So stubborn.

27:47.000 --> 27:48.959
Which I would say comes from her mother...

27:49.041 --> 27:50.250
-Mm.
-...but I think we both know...

27:50.333 --> 27:51.583
-50/50 split.
-...right down the middle.

27:51.667 --> 27:53.458
Yeah.

27:53.542 --> 27:55.625
I could never give that up
going to Boston.

27:55.709 --> 27:58.583
Sea creature alarm clocks,
holding her when she's sick.

27:58.667 --> 28:00.125
But I can't walk away from this chance

28:00.208 --> 28:01.792
to make real change in the foundation.

28:01.875 --> 28:04.417
I mean, Mom was able to do both.

28:04.500 --> 28:06.500
And I know in my gut, that I can, too.

28:06.583 --> 28:08.959
I mean, I owe it to Harriet
to try, at least.

28:09.041 --> 28:10.959
-I know.
-And I know I can't do it all,

28:11.041 --> 28:12.834
but, April, I am telling you,

28:13.208 --> 28:15.792
I can take this foundation
to a whole new chapter.

28:15.959 --> 28:18.417
I mean, creating real
racial equity in medicine.

28:18.500 --> 28:19.500
Are you kidding?

28:19.583 --> 28:21.917
It's a revolutionary, lasting change.

28:22.208 --> 28:24.000
I could look my daughter in the face

28:24.083 --> 28:26.041
and know that I've done
everything I possibly can

28:26.125 --> 28:27.834
to give her a better world.

28:27.917 --> 28:29.875
I know. I know.

28:30.875 --> 28:32.208
I could do all that

28:32.291 --> 28:34.500
and -- and be the father
that mine never was.

28:37.875 --> 28:40.709
And all I need to do
is turn my life upside down.

28:47.583 --> 28:51.458
[ Birds chirping ]

28:58.625 --> 29:00.792
Puts a lot into perspective, huh?

29:05.458 --> 29:08.667
Yeah, I come out here every morning
just to take it all in.

29:10.333 --> 29:12.333
Feel like I got a lot more thinking done

29:12.417 --> 29:13.875
these last few days out here

29:13.959 --> 29:16.166
than probably [Chuckling] all year.

29:19.250 --> 29:20.792
Might find it hard to believe,

29:20.875 --> 29:23.667
but I've been thinking a lot
about our last visit.

29:23.750 --> 29:25.083
Everything you said.

29:26.625 --> 29:28.083
And the truth is,

29:28.166 --> 29:30.125
I left because that's what I do.

29:30.542 --> 29:32.583
I chose this place because it's safe.

29:33.291 --> 29:36.583
Running the restaurant, bagging lunches,

29:36.834 --> 29:39.125
none of it requires much of me.

29:39.583 --> 29:42.417
I can walk away
and not look back any time.

29:45.500 --> 29:47.750
And just forget about who
you're leaving behind, yeah?

29:47.834 --> 29:50.041
I was convinced you were
better off without me.

29:50.125 --> 29:51.166
Without a father?

29:51.250 --> 29:53.709
How would you think
I'm better off without...

29:54.542 --> 29:57.750
my father never being there
for any birthdays,

29:57.834 --> 29:59.125
any graduations?

29:59.291 --> 30:02.333
That time I got beat up by Billy Paxton?

30:02.875 --> 30:04.333
At my wedding?

30:04.417 --> 30:07.125
The birth of my child, your granddaughter.

30:07.542 --> 30:09.417
My divorce -- maybe that
would've been a good time

30:09.500 --> 30:12.333
for you to step in and share some wisdom.

30:13.041 --> 30:14.542
A hug, I don't know.

30:14.625 --> 30:16.250
Help me make some decisions?

30:16.333 --> 30:19.625
It's not like it was a few months, man.

30:20.000 --> 30:21.583
Or a year or 10 years.

30:21.667 --> 30:22.834
It's my entire life.

30:22.917 --> 30:25.417
-How could you think that's better?
-In my father's eyes,

30:25.834 --> 30:27.583
I was the screw-up in the family,

30:27.667 --> 30:28.917
and I absorbed that story.

30:29.000 --> 30:30.625
Maybe I became it.

30:30.709 --> 30:32.959
And I didn't want
to pass that down to you.

30:33.333 --> 30:35.166
: I did not want to mess you up.

30:36.375 --> 30:38.917
[ Scoffs ] Congrats.

30:39.000 --> 30:40.208
Robert: I get that now.

30:40.291 --> 30:41.959
I hurt a lot of people.

30:43.083 --> 30:45.166
You, your mother.

30:46.291 --> 30:49.041
And to have found out
I have a granddaughter that I...

30:52.166 --> 30:53.458
may never meet...

30:53.542 --> 30:55.583
Yeah, well, it didn't have to
be that way, did it?

30:55.667 --> 30:57.333
Robert: You're absolutely right.

30:57.417 --> 30:59.083
So I buy her presents.

30:59.166 --> 31:02.542
An art set, a basketball,
tricycle, board games.

31:02.625 --> 31:04.417
What are you saying?
And you didn't send them?

31:04.500 --> 31:05.500
I don't have the right.

31:05.750 --> 31:06.959
I don't deserve...

31:07.959 --> 31:11.291
to take your time, be in your space.

31:13.166 --> 31:15.417
Not one day has passed

31:15.500 --> 31:18.333
that I haven't regretted leaving you.

31:18.417 --> 31:20.583
It haunts me in my sleep,

31:21.000 --> 31:22.917
when I wake up in the morning.

31:23.000 --> 31:25.166
And I am truly, truly sorry.

31:25.250 --> 31:28.333
And yet I know an apology
will never make up for it.

31:28.417 --> 31:30.291
And I have to live with that.

31:31.083 --> 31:32.959
I will never get over it.

31:35.208 --> 31:37.041
Oh, Jackson.

31:37.125 --> 31:39.625
Crossroads like this,
you don't arrive at them often,

31:39.709 --> 31:41.834
but I know you will be okay,

31:42.500 --> 31:44.291
no matter what road you choose.

31:45.166 --> 31:46.875
I'm still an Avery, right?

31:46.959 --> 31:48.291
I still find some way to...

31:48.875 --> 31:50.000
walk away from it all.

31:50.083 --> 31:51.583
Apple doesn't fall far from the tree.

31:51.667 --> 31:52.792
Isn't that what they say?

31:52.875 --> 31:55.041
-[ Chuckles ]
-Nice.

31:55.125 --> 31:56.959
-That's great.
-No, I'm sorry.

31:57.041 --> 31:58.500
I just thought that was funny.

31:58.583 --> 32:00.333
I'm the tree, you're the apple.

32:01.291 --> 32:02.542
Do you really think that?

32:03.000 --> 32:04.417
I'm sitting here, aren't I?

32:04.500 --> 32:07.458
Jackson, let me assure you,
you are not me.

32:07.542 --> 32:09.750
The fact that you're even
questioning your choices

32:09.834 --> 32:11.250
is proof of that.

32:11.333 --> 32:12.500
And if that's not enough,

32:12.583 --> 32:14.417
you are committed, Jackson.

32:14.500 --> 32:17.875
Committed to your work, to your family,
to people in need.

32:20.000 --> 32:22.417
And I know sometimes you want
to run away from it all,

32:22.500 --> 32:24.542
but anybody with any sense does that.

32:24.959 --> 32:28.208
It's very different
from actually following through with it.

32:29.917 --> 32:31.417
I was scared.

32:32.375 --> 32:33.625
I'm scared.

32:33.709 --> 32:36.166
Yeah, but you're scared
of doing the <i>wrong </i>thing.

32:36.625 --> 32:39.667
I was too scared to do the <i>right </i>thing.

32:42.125 --> 32:43.458
You're not a runner.

32:43.542 --> 32:45.625
If you were, you would have been
long gone by now.

32:45.792 --> 32:47.000
Do you know how easy it would have been

32:47.083 --> 32:48.375
for you to walk away from everything

32:48.458 --> 32:50.583
after it all came out
about the foundation?

32:50.667 --> 32:52.583
Did you even consider it?

32:54.792 --> 32:56.041
Not really, no.

32:56.125 --> 32:57.417
Of course not.

32:57.500 --> 32:59.959
'Cause you have it in your soul
to do the right thing,

33:00.041 --> 33:01.625
to make things right.

33:01.709 --> 33:03.291
And you didn't just fix a disaster,

33:03.375 --> 33:04.583
you made it better.

33:05.417 --> 33:08.709
So if you don't want to stay, don't.

33:08.792 --> 33:10.583
But don't blame it on me.

33:13.500 --> 33:15.000
'Cause on your worst day,

33:15.083 --> 33:17.291
you are 10 times the man I am.

33:28.208 --> 33:31.417
[ Thunder crashes ]

33:38.542 --> 33:40.125
-Jackson?
-Hey.

33:40.208 --> 33:41.333
-Come in.
-I can't stay.

33:41.417 --> 33:42.959
Honey, it's pouring out here.

33:43.041 --> 33:44.083
Here, Mom.

33:44.166 --> 33:45.875
I mean, I can't stay
at Grey-Sloan in Seattle.

33:45.959 --> 33:47.709
I can't keep doing what we've always done.

33:47.792 --> 33:49.125
You know how many people of color

33:49.208 --> 33:50.917
we've already lost
since the pandemic started?

33:51.000 --> 33:53.000
The system keeps diminishing
and erasing us.

33:53.083 --> 33:55.375
T-They're literally letting
people just die in the streets,

33:55.458 --> 33:56.583
and we can do something about it.

33:56.667 --> 33:58.250
I got to show Harriet
that we can put our money

33:58.333 --> 34:00.000
and our attention where our mouths are.

34:00.083 --> 34:01.834
And we can acknowledge
the connection between our work

34:01.917 --> 34:03.250
and what's actually happening
in the streets

34:03.333 --> 34:06.375
and give a sense of equity
in this world, okay?

34:06.458 --> 34:08.166
It's not gonna change after COVID.

34:08.250 --> 34:09.959
We know that.

34:10.041 --> 34:12.500
White supremacy is woven into
the fabric of this country,

34:12.583 --> 34:14.250
and that means medicine, too.

34:14.333 --> 34:15.834
[ Sighs ] People that look like us

34:15.959 --> 34:18.333
should not have to be
gaslit, shamed, and ignored

34:18.417 --> 34:19.792
when they're just going to the doctor,

34:19.875 --> 34:21.875
constantly having to prove
that their lives have any value.

34:21.959 --> 34:24.125
It's like this constant cycle of stress

34:24.208 --> 34:26.375
from poverty and trauma and racism,

34:26.458 --> 34:28.917
and it's definitely
impacting mental health --

34:29.000 --> 34:30.667
it's definitely killing us.

34:30.750 --> 34:32.041
Where are people supposed to turn?

34:32.125 --> 34:33.417
They don't feel safe going to the doctor.

34:33.500 --> 34:35.250
They're scared to call the cops.

34:35.375 --> 34:37.500
This is like a deep-seated neglect.

34:37.583 --> 34:40.250
And if our deaths are not
affecting their profit margin,

34:40.333 --> 34:42.000
then it's not gonna change.

34:44.750 --> 34:46.000
I want to take over the foundation.

34:46.083 --> 34:47.667
What?

34:47.750 --> 34:49.083
I want to reallocate
every penny that we have

34:49.166 --> 34:50.583
to equity in medicine --

34:50.667 --> 34:52.834
women's health, trans health,
racial equity.

34:52.917 --> 34:56.667
I want everyone who this country
abuses to be served, okay?

34:56.750 --> 34:59.083
We need to challenge
all the ways that we teach,

34:59.166 --> 35:00.792
everything that we're doing.

35:00.875 --> 35:03.291
If that means dismantling
the whole medical system

35:03.375 --> 35:05.875
a-and -- and designing something
that actually serves everyone,

35:05.959 --> 35:07.333
then that's what I want to do.

35:07.417 --> 35:08.583
I-I see that now. I'm ready.

35:08.667 --> 35:10.500
Jackson, where have you been?

35:10.583 --> 35:12.041
It doesn't even matter anymore, Mom.

35:12.125 --> 35:14.250
It matters that I'm back
and I know where I belong.

35:14.333 --> 35:15.583
Oh!

35:15.667 --> 35:16.959
-I gotta go. I love you.
-Ah!

35:17.083 --> 35:18.709
[ Smooches ] Where on God's earth
are you going now?

35:18.792 --> 35:20.125
I got to go talk to April.

35:20.208 --> 35:21.709
What?! Jackson...

35:21.792 --> 35:23.417
[ Thunder crashing ]

35:28.959 --> 35:31.333
Here we go. Yummy!

35:31.417 --> 35:33.000
Are you gonna go with crazy fork?

35:33.667 --> 35:34.709
[ Exhales sharply ]

35:34.792 --> 35:37.291
Pancakes go in your belly.

35:37.375 --> 35:38.709
Why do you always go for the big ones?

35:38.792 --> 35:39.750
[Harriet speaking indistinctly]

35:39.834 --> 35:41.834
-Take all the small pieces, alright?
-[ Sighs ]

35:41.917 --> 35:43.250
You want to cut
your own little piece?

35:43.333 --> 35:44.333
-Harriet: A small one.
-Jackson: What are you doing --

35:44.417 --> 35:46.750
a small one this time,
that's soaked up in syrup?

35:46.834 --> 35:48.208
Extra syrup?

35:48.291 --> 35:49.583
Ooh. There she is.

35:49.709 --> 35:51.583
-There she is.
-Hi!

35:51.667 --> 35:52.834
Harriet: Mommy!

35:52.917 --> 35:55.417
[ Laughs ] Hi!

35:55.500 --> 35:57.125
-Oh!
-No fever.

35:57.208 --> 35:59.959
Oh, good, good, good.

36:00.041 --> 36:01.291
I want orange juice.

36:01.375 --> 36:02.875
Yeah, you can have some orange juice.

36:02.959 --> 36:04.291
You want me to get it for you, baby?

36:04.375 --> 36:05.542
No, I get it myself.

36:05.625 --> 36:06.917
-[ Chuckles ] Okay.
-Jackson: Okay.

36:07.000 --> 36:08.291
[ Laughs ]

36:08.375 --> 36:10.000
Go ahead, baby.

36:10.083 --> 36:12.500
Are you gonna unscrew the top and pour it?

36:16.667 --> 36:19.041
April: You are that guy, Jackson.

36:19.750 --> 36:22.125
I was an ass for saying otherwise.

36:22.208 --> 36:23.458
Yeah?

36:25.083 --> 36:26.959
Pillows in every room. [ Chuckles ]

36:27.041 --> 36:28.667
They come in handy.

36:29.041 --> 36:31.125
Hey, are you sure about this?

36:31.875 --> 36:33.333
I'm not sure it's gonna work, but...

36:33.417 --> 36:35.291
I'm sure it's what I want, yeah.

36:36.125 --> 36:38.834
Why is our timing always so terrible?

36:39.125 --> 36:41.083
I thought that was kind of
our thing -- bad timing.

36:41.166 --> 36:42.500
We just never figured out

36:42.583 --> 36:44.709
how to want the same thing
at the same time.

36:44.792 --> 36:45.959
Even with Harriet.

36:46.166 --> 36:48.875
Yeah, but, I mean,
it worked out pretty well.

36:49.375 --> 36:50.792
Yeah, but we were fighting,

36:50.875 --> 36:52.166
and then we had sex

36:52.250 --> 36:53.959
while our marriage was falling apart.

36:54.458 --> 36:55.875
That was actually our thing --

36:56.000 --> 36:58.500
arguing until we were blue
in the face and then having sex.

36:58.583 --> 37:00.625
Yeah, I guess we were doomed, huh?

37:01.458 --> 37:04.792
Look, if you're really
living your dream here,

37:04.875 --> 37:06.625
I'll give it up, because you're right.

37:06.709 --> 37:08.125
I'm totally springing it on you guys.

37:08.208 --> 37:09.125
No. What?

37:09.208 --> 37:11.041
You do not get to do all the speeches

37:11.125 --> 37:12.208
and the convincing

37:12.291 --> 37:15.000
and that thing where your face
just lights up

37:15.083 --> 37:16.208
just to take it all back again.

37:16.291 --> 37:17.417
Don't take it all back.

37:18.125 --> 37:19.792
You deserve this.

37:20.208 --> 37:21.834
Wait. What are you saying?

37:21.917 --> 37:23.417
I am saying...

37:24.959 --> 37:27.250
...we will make Boston work.

37:28.458 --> 37:30.083
I'm saying yes.

37:30.166 --> 37:32.166
What? You're saying yes?

37:32.250 --> 37:33.417
-To my question, you're saying yes?
-Yes.

37:33.500 --> 37:35.625
I'm saying -- Yeah. I thought
that's what you wanted.

37:35.709 --> 37:37.375
Yeah, but -- Yes?

37:37.458 --> 37:39.667
Like, I didn't think
it would be that easy.

37:39.750 --> 37:41.458
I'm sorry. You call this night easy?

37:41.542 --> 37:42.917
No, not -- not easy like that,

37:43.000 --> 37:46.166
but, like, I thought [chuckles]
you'd have to pray

37:46.250 --> 37:49.041
or consult with Matthew,
maybe get your pastor involved,

37:49.125 --> 37:51.375
-some additional praying...
-Yeah. Yeah. Matthew will be fine.

37:51.458 --> 37:53.041
-[ Sighs ]
-Alright, well, when does he get back?

37:53.125 --> 37:54.792
I can help with the pitch.
I can talk to him.

37:54.875 --> 37:56.917
-What do you want me to...?
-Uh, no. No. No.

37:57.000 --> 37:58.834
No, that's a horrible and weird idea...

37:58.917 --> 38:00.166
[Yeah.
-Yes... obviously.

38:00.250 --> 38:02.041
Um, but tell him that
I can help him with work.

38:02.125 --> 38:03.959
I'll make sure everything is
arranged for him and for Ruby.

38:04.041 --> 38:05.291
We split up.

38:09.500 --> 38:10.750
Oh.

38:18.333 --> 38:22.000
April: We kept trying to tell ourselves
that our whole winding road

38:22.083 --> 38:24.917
was God's plan to bring us back together.

38:25.000 --> 38:26.208
[ Breathes deeply ]

38:26.291 --> 38:29.208
But he was still so angry and so hurt.

38:30.542 --> 38:33.583
I mean, I left him at the altar,
and then his wife died.

38:33.667 --> 38:35.709
You know, you don't just stop feeling hurt

38:35.792 --> 38:37.417
'cause it's a better story

38:37.500 --> 38:40.333
if God brought us together in our pain.

38:41.291 --> 38:42.834
He denied it for so long.

38:42.917 --> 38:45.917
You know, he tried so hard not to hate me.

38:46.000 --> 38:49.583
I think loving me, making us a full circle

38:49.667 --> 38:51.959
was the story he was writing.

38:52.083 --> 38:54.625
I mean, I guess it was the story
we were both writing.

38:54.709 --> 38:56.166
I mean, I was trying to get past my guilt.

38:56.250 --> 38:58.125
He was -- He was trying to forgive God

38:58.208 --> 39:00.208
for the loss of Karin.

39:03.709 --> 39:06.875
But, y-you know,
ultimately, we learned that...

39:08.417 --> 39:09.667
[ Chuckles ]

39:10.041 --> 39:14.166
...life just isn't always so tidy.

39:17.500 --> 39:20.750
And God's plan isn't always
so easy to understand.

39:22.166 --> 39:23.792
He's always been so good with Harriet,

39:23.875 --> 39:25.375
and I adore Ruby,

39:25.458 --> 39:27.542
but we both started working longer hours,

39:27.625 --> 39:29.208
just avoiding coming home.

39:29.291 --> 39:31.500
And then, his sister got sick.
She lives in Philadelphia.

39:31.583 --> 39:34.250
So he and Ruby went to
Philadelphia to be with her,

39:34.333 --> 39:36.417
and...now she's better,

39:36.500 --> 39:39.125
uh, but they're still in Philadelphia.
[ Chuckles ]

39:40.542 --> 39:41.792
And...

39:43.250 --> 39:44.709
they are not coming back.

39:48.667 --> 39:50.458
I had no idea.

39:52.125 --> 39:53.792
Yeah, I mean, I was gonna tell you,

39:53.875 --> 39:56.458
but, you know, hundreds of
thousands of people were dying.

39:56.542 --> 40:00.291
I just didn't think my marriage
counted as a casualty.

40:00.667 --> 40:04.417
And you were maybe
a little too proud to tell me?

40:05.375 --> 40:06.917
-Yeah, fine.
-[ Chuckles ]

40:07.000 --> 40:08.709
I was a little -- a little too proud.

40:11.375 --> 40:12.667
You okay?

40:16.041 --> 40:17.417
It's hard to say.

40:20.291 --> 40:21.500
But...

40:22.458 --> 40:24.625
it looks like I'm moving to Boston.

40:24.709 --> 40:26.208
[ Chuckles ]

40:26.291 --> 40:27.291
So...

40:27.375 --> 40:28.959
[ Humming ]

40:29.041 --> 40:31.709
Fingers crossed for new horizons.

40:32.750 --> 40:34.875
Fingers crossed for new horizons.

40:35.417 --> 40:38.291
<i>♪ I know you're out there,</i>
<i>doin' the best you can ♪</i>

40:38.375 --> 40:39.875
Jackson: <i>No one said it was easy,</i>

40:39.959 --> 40:41.750
<i>becoming the person you're meant to be.</i>

40:41.834 --> 40:45.000
<i>♪ But everybody needs a helping hand ♪</i>

40:45.125 --> 40:48.041
<i>It takes bravery a step into</i>
<i>the power you found</i>

40:48.125 --> 40:50.208
<i>and earned and deserve.</i>

40:50.291 --> 40:52.041
<i>♪ 'Cause we're all alone</i>
<i>in this together ♪</i>

40:52.125 --> 40:53.417
<i>♪ But the storm won't last forever ♪</i>

40:53.500 --> 40:54.959
Richard: He'll come back.

40:55.041 --> 40:57.625
And you'll visit, and he'll visit.

40:57.709 --> 40:58.834
I know.

40:58.917 --> 41:00.667
Richard: You know, it's okay to be sad.

41:01.125 --> 41:04.125
It's hard handing over something
you put your life into.

41:04.250 --> 41:05.667
<i>♪ So much light ♪</i>

41:05.750 --> 41:07.291
[ Voice breaking ] I'm not sad.

41:07.750 --> 41:12.375
It's just, like, I never in my life

41:13.125 --> 41:16.667
felt pride quite like this.

41:16.917 --> 41:18.417
<i>♪ We can hold each other up ♪</i>

41:20.542 --> 41:25.208
<i>♪ We can hold each other up ♪</i>

41:25.917 --> 41:28.625
<i>♪ Yeah ♪</i>

41:28.709 --> 41:30.709
<i>♪ Hold each other up ♪</i>

41:30.792 --> 41:33.875
Jackson: <i>The trick is, to take the</i>
<i>people who were there for you,</i>

41:33.959 --> 41:35.041
<i>with you.</i>

41:35.125 --> 41:37.041
<i>To remind you you're not alone.</i>

41:37.125 --> 41:38.667
It's gonna take a few days,

41:38.750 --> 41:40.583
figure out what to tell the chief.

41:41.208 --> 41:43.208
Feels weird to say Boston.

41:44.083 --> 41:45.500
[ Scoffs ] Feels like a...

41:45.583 --> 41:47.041
[ Door creaks ]

41:47.709 --> 41:48.917
I don't know.

41:49.000 --> 41:52.083
It feels "I don't know" to me, too.

41:52.166 --> 41:54.417
<i>♪ 'Cause I see hope in togetherness ♪</i>

41:54.500 --> 41:56.375
-Thank you.
-Oh!

41:56.625 --> 41:57.542
<i>♪ So much light ♪</i>

41:57.625 --> 41:58.667
Harriet: Mommy, Daddy!

41:58.750 --> 41:59.875
<i>♪ And so much love ♪</i>

41:59.959 --> 42:00.959
I got her.

42:01.041 --> 42:02.000
You go.

42:02.083 --> 42:03.166
Get ready to go.

42:03.250 --> 42:05.208
<i>♪ There is strength,</i>
<i>strength in tenderness ♪</i>

42:05.291 --> 42:06.583
[ Door closes ]

42:07.458 --> 42:10.667
Jackson: <i>You have an entire</i>
<i>legacy behind you</i>

42:10.750 --> 42:12.375
<i>as you create your own.</i>

42:12.750 --> 42:17.959
<i>♪ We can hold each other up ♪</i>

42:29.375 --> 42:32.709
[ Closing theme music playing ]
